{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-8c04da3c9a14940f", "type": "tool_result", "content": "# wav2vec 2.0: A Framework for Self-Supervised Learning of Speech Representations\narXiv: 2006.11477\nAuthors: Alexei Baevski, Henry Zhou, Abdelrahman Mohamed, Michael Auli\nYear: 2020 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_representation\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Proposes a self-supervised speech representation framework that masks latent speech representations and solves a contrastive task over jointly learned quantized speech units.\n  2. Demonstrates that self-supervised pre-training followed by fine-tuning outperforms the best semi-supervised methods while being conceptually simpler.\n  3. Achieves state-of-the-art word error rates on the full Librispeech benchmark when using all labeled data.\n  4. Shows the feasibility of ultra-low resource speech recognition by outperforming the previous state of the art on the 100-hour subset while using 100 times less labeled data.\n  5. Achieves strong word error rates using only ten minutes of labeled data combined with unlabeled pre-training data.\n  6. Sets a new state of the art on TIMIT phoneme recognition.\n  7. Shows that using continuous latent representations as input and quantized representations as contrastive targets performs substantially better than quantizing both.\n\nTags: SSL, ASR, SSL/对比式\n---2512.20151---\n# QuarkAudio Technical Report\narXiv: 2512.20151\nAuthors: Chengwei Liu, Haoyin Yan, Shaofei Xue, Xiaotao Liang, Xiaofu Chen, Bin Gong, Zheng Xue, Gang Song\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We present H-Codec, a unified discrete audio tokenizer that integrates self-supervised learning representations into the tokenization process via dual-stream (acoustic and semantic) quantization, achieving remarkable audio reconstruction quality at a low frame rate.\n  2. We introduce advanced H-Codec variants, including H-Codec-1.5 with a dynamic frame-rate mechanism for adaptive temporal resolution and H-Codec-2.0 extending the sampling rate to 48 kHz for higher fidelity.\n  3. We propose QuarkAudio, a unified decoder-only autoregressive language model framework that uses task-specific conditional information and special task tokens to distinguish and unify multiple audio processing and generation tasks within a single set of shared weights.\n  4. We extend unified audio generation to universal free-form audio editing guided by natural language instructions, covering both speech semantic editing and audio event editing.\n  5. We demonstrate that QuarkAudio achieves competitive or comparable high-fidelity generation performance against state-of-the-art task-specific or multi-task systems across speech restoration, target speaker extraction, speech separation, voice conversion, and language-queried audio source separation tasks.\n\nTags: TTS, TTS/架构-AR-LLM, TTS/功能-语音编辑, TTS/功能-多任务统一, 压缩, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-语义, 压缩/语义声学-声学", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "e3f12ddc-4106-4f48-8a58-5c7df4d279a9", "uuid": "f6d0446d-79ad-4887-b5c9-39409d7b44d2", "timestamp": "2026-07-06T14:10:18.242Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "# wav2vec 2.0: A Framework for Self-Supervised Learning of Speech Representations\narXiv: 2006.11477\nAuthors: Alexei Baevski, Henry Zhou, Abdelrahman Mohamed, Michael Auli\nYear: 2020 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_representation\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Proposes a self-supervised speech representation framework that masks latent speech representations and solves a contrastive task over jointly learned quantized speech units.\n  2. Demonstrates that self-supervised pre-training followed by fine-tuning outperforms the best semi-supervised methods while being conceptually simpler.\n  3. Achieves state-of-the-art word error rates on the full Librispeech benchmark when using all labeled data.\n  4. Shows the feasibility of ultra-low resource speech recognition by outperforming the previous state of the art on the 100-hour subset while using 100 times less labeled data.\n  5. Achieves strong word error rates using only ten minutes of labeled data combined with unlabeled pre-training data.\n  6. Sets a new state of the art on TIMIT phoneme recognition.\n  7. Shows that using continuous latent representations as input and quantized representations as contrastive targets performs substantially better than quantizing both.\n\nTags: SSL, ASR, SSL/对比式\n---2512.20151---\n# QuarkAudio Technical Report\narXiv: 2512.20151\nAuthors: Chengwei Liu, Haoyin Yan, Shaofei Xue, Xiaotao Liang, Xiaofu Chen, Bin Gong, Zheng Xue, Gang Song\nYear: 2025 | Venue: \nTopic: codec_vae\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. We present H-Codec, a unified discrete audio tokenizer that integrates self-supervised learning representations into the tokenization process via dual-stream (acoustic and semantic) quantization, achieving remarkable audio reconstruction quality at a low frame rate.\n  2. We introduce advanced H-Codec variants, including H-Codec-1.5 with a dynamic frame-rate mechanism for adaptive temporal resolution and H-Codec-2.0 extending the sampling rate to 48 kHz for higher fidelity.\n  3. We propose QuarkAudio, a unified decoder-only autoregressive language model framework that uses task-specific conditional information and special task tokens to distinguish and unify multiple audio processing and generation tasks within a single set of shared weights.\n  4. We extend unified audio generation to universal free-form audio editing guided by natural language instructions, covering both speech semantic editing and audio event editing.\n  5. We demonstrate that QuarkAudio achieves competitive or comparable high-fidelity generation performance against state-of-the-art task-specific or multi-task systems across speech restoration, target speaker extraction, speech separation, voice conversion, and language-queried audio source separation tasks.\n\nTags: TTS, TTS/架构-AR-LLM, TTS/功能-语音编辑, TTS/功能-多任务统一, 压缩, 压缩/量化-RVQ, 压缩/语义声学-语义, 压缩/语义声学-声学", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
