{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a1adad703fdcbdf4", "type": "tool_result", "content": "100\tburst-aware adaptation on completed blocks and applies the\n101\t\n102\t\f2\n103\t\n104\tIEEE/ACM TRANSACTIONS ON AUDIO, SPEECH, AND LANGUAGE PROCESSING\n105\t\n106\tupdated model only to future audio. For music PLC, we study\n107\twhether a model trained for one signal class can adapt on the\n108\tcurrent file when the test signal is in domain or out of domain.\n109\tWe use streaming every-packet adaptation with held-out snapshot selection, so the model is updated from received packets\n110\twhile the deployed checkpoint is chosen without access to\n111\tthe true losses. We evaluate the approach across speech and\n112\tmusic backbones, non-causal and causal deployment settings,\n113\tin-domain and out-of-domain signals, ablations, and runtime\n114\tmeasurements. The code and experiment scripts are available\n115\tpublicly. 1\n116\tII. R ELATED W ORK\n117\tPacket loss concealment (PLC) is the receiver-side task\n118\tof reconstructing missing audio packets from the packets\n119\tthat arrived. Classical PLC methods were designed for lowcomplexity, low-latency communication systems. The G.711\n120\tAppendix I standard [1] uses waveform substitution and attenuation to conceal short erasures. Linear-prediction methods\n121\tsuch as Gunduzhan and Momtahan [7] estimate the missing\n122\twaveform from the recent past, while waveform extrapolation\n123\tand overlap-add approaches such as Chen [8] exploit local\n124\ttemporal continuity. Modern codecs also include packet-loss\n125\trobustness internally; Opus [2] combines linear prediction,\n126\ttransform coding, and concealment tools for interactive speech\n127\tand audio. These signal-processing methods remain attractive\n128\tbecause of their speed and stability, but their behavior is\n129\tfixed by design and cannot specialize to a particular speaker,\n130\tinstrument, recording, or loss pattern at deployment time.\n131\tDeep PLC methods learn a data-driven prior for missing\n132\taudio. Early neural approaches formulated PLC as futureframe prediction or regression from local context. Lin et al. [9]\n133\tuse convolutional and recurrent networks for time-domain\n134\treconstruction, and Westhausen and Meyer [10] developed a\n135\ttime-domain PLC model, tPLCnet, that uses recurrent neural networks to predict missing waveform samples from a\n136\tshort causal context. Generative approaches have also been\n137\texplored: Pascual et al. [11] use adversarial auto-encoding for\n138\tpacket-loss recovery, and Wang et al. [12] propose a temporalspectral GAN to synthesize plausible missing regions. Nguyen\n139\tet al. [5] introduced FRN, which performs full-band blind\n140\tspeech PLC with a recurrent frequency-domain model, avoiding the need for an explicit loss mask at inference. For\n141\tnetworked music, PARCnet [6] combines a classical autoregressive predictor with a neural residual branch to meet lowlatency musical constraints. Recent diffusion and flow-based\n142\tPLC methods, such as Diff-PLC [13] and Flow-PLC [14],\n143\tfurther improve the expressiveness of neural concealment by\n144\tmodeling richer conditional reconstruction distributions. These\n145\tmethods differ in architecture and training objective, but they\n146\tare usually used as fixed pretrained systems at test time.\n147\tPLC evaluation has also become more standardized. The\n148\tINTERSPEECH 2022 Audio Deep PLC Challenge [3] introduced a public benchmark with realistic loss traces collected\n149\tfrom communication scenarios, and the ICASSP 2024 Audio\n150\tDeep PLC Challenge [15] continued this line of evaluation.\n151\t1 https://github.com/MLSpeech/TTT-PLC\n152\t\n153\tPLCMOS [4] provides a learned perceptual metric targeted\n154\tspecifically at PLC artifacts, complementing traditional intrusive metrics such as PESQ [16] and STOI [17]. Controlled\n155\texperiments often use bursty loss models such as Gilbert–\n156\tElliott [18] to approximate clustered packet drops. These\n157\tbenchmarks and metrics are important for test-time adaptation because the amount of useful received signal, the burst\n158\tstructure, and the local loss density can all affect whether\n159\tadaptation helps or hurts. Several recent works connect PLC\n160\twith automatic speech recognition. Yang and Chang [19]\n161\tuse an ASR-oriented auxiliary loss to guide PLC toward\n162\treconstructions that preserve recognition-relevant information.\n163\tZhang et al. [20] introduce semantic awareness into PLC,\n164\tusing linguistic context to improve reconstruction during long\n165\tpacket-loss bursts. Dissen et al. [21], [22] focused on PLC for\n166\timproving ASR by training a front-end PLC network guided\n167\tby a frozen ASR model.\n168\tSelf-supervised learning provides a way to train models\n169\tfrom structure available in the input rather than from manual\n170\tlabels. Noise2Void [23] and Noise2Self [24] show that denoisers can be trained by predicting held-out observations from\n171\ttheir context. Test-time adaptation updates model parameters\n172\tduring inference to better match the current input distribution.\n173\tTent [25] adapts image classifiers by minimizing prediction\n174\tentropy on unlabeled test data. Related approaches in speech\n175\tuse unlabeled objectives for zero-shot denoising or dereverberation [26]. In our setting, the unlabeled test input has a special\n176\tstructure: some packets are missing and cannot be used for loss\n177\tcomputation, while other packets are received and can be used\n178\tto define a self-supervised concealment task. This differs from\n179\tstandard test-time adaptation, where the input is usually fully\n180\tobserved but unlabeled. It also creates different deployment\n181\tconstraints: in the causal setting, adaptation may use only past\n182\treceived audio and must not revise already-emitted samples.\n183\tDeep Image Prior [27] demonstrates that an untrained\n184\tconvolutional network can regularize inverse problems when\n185\toptimized to fit the observed pixels of a single corrupted image. Deep Decoder [28] shows that compact untrained neural\n186\tarchitectures can act as image priors. NeRF [29] optimizes a\n187\tneural radiance field to fit the observations of a single scene,\n188\tshowing the potential of per-instance neural fitting. In inverse\n189\tproblems, ZS-SSL [30] partitions acquired MRI measurements\n190\tinto disjoint subsets for self-supervised reconstruction without\n191\tfully sampled reference data. Our approach follows the perinstance optimization philosophy but differs from these methods in two ways: it starts from a pretrained PLC model rather\n192\tthan fitting a new representation from scratch, and it trains on\n193\ta proxy concealment task constructed from received packets\n194\twhile evaluating on the true packet losses.\n195\tIII. M ETHOD\n196\tThis study proposes a test-time adaptation framework for\n197\tpacket loss concealment that improves pretrained PLC models\n198\twithout changing their architectures or using additional training data. As described earlier, most neural PLC systems are\n199\tdeployed as fixed models: a corrupted audio stream is passed\n200\tthrough the pretrained concealer, and the model parameters\n201\t\n202\t\fDISSEN AND KESHET: TEST-TIME TUNING FOR PACKET LOSS CONCEALMENT\n203\t\n204\tremain unchanged for every call, recording, or packet-loss\n205\tpattern. This is limiting because the received portions of the\n206\ttest signal contain information about the speaker, instrument,\n207\tchannel, and local temporal structure of the current file.\n208\tHere, we use that information directly by constructing a selfsupervised PLC task from the packets that were successfully\n209\treceived. Specifically, we synthetically mask a subset of the\n210\tavailable packets, train the model to reconstruct them using\n211\tits native PLC objective, and then use the adapted model to\n212\tconceal the true packet losses.\n213\tWe start by presenting the notation and general setting. We\n214\tuse the term packet to denote the unit on which the loss\n215\tmask is defined. For the FRN model [5] this unit is an STFT\n216\tframe, whereas for the PARCnet model [6] this unit is a 10 ms\n217\twaveform packet. Let x1:T = (x1 , . . . , xT ) denote the clean\n218\tpacket sequence, where xt ∈ RN , and let m1:T ∈ {0, 1}T\n219\tdenote the packet-loss mask. We use mt = 1 for a true packet\n220\tloss and mt = 0 for a packet that arrived at the receiver.\n221\tThis defines two disjoint sets. The first set is the set of speech\n222\tframes which are originally lost and is denoted L. The second\n223\tset is the set of the observed frames, denoted by O. That is\n224\tL = {t : mt = 1},\n225\tO = {t : mt = 0},\n226\t\n227\t(1)\n228\t\n229\twhere L ∩ O = ∅ and L ∪ O = {1, . . . , T }. The clean packet\n230\txt is available to the receiver only for t ∈ O. Frames (or\n231\tpackets) in L are used only for final evaluation and are never\n232\tused as adaptation targets.\n233\tLet fθ be a pretrained PLC model with parameters θ. Given\n234\tthe context available at frame or packet index t, denoted by\n235\tut , the model predicts the lost packet xt\n236\tx̂t = fθ (ut ).\n237\t\n238\t(2)\n239\t\n240\tNote that is the packet at time t is observed the model should\n241\treturn it as is. The context ut depends on the backbone. It\n242\tmay contain past waveform samples, STFT frames, recurrent\n243\tstates, an autoregressive buffer, or a combination of these. Let\n244\tℓ(x̂t , xt ) denote the native PLC loss used to train and find the\n245\tparameters θ of the pretrained model fθ .\n246\tThe proposed method creates a self-supervised PLC task\n247\tfrom the observed packets. We choose subsets of O, mask\n248\tthem synthetically, and train the model to reconstruct them.\n249\tThe true lost packets L remain masked during adaptation and\n250\tare not used in the loss.\n251\tA. Non-causal test-time tuning\n252\tIn the non-causal setting, the complete received file is\n253\tavailable before final reconstruction. We adapt a separate copy\n254\tof the pretrained model for each test file and reset the model\n255\tto the public checkpoint before moving to the next file.\n256\tWe first partition the observed packets into a held-out\n257\tvalidation set and an adaptation pool. Specifically, we sample\n258\ta held-out set H ⊂ O, where H contains packets that\n259\tarrived at the receiver but are not used for gradient updates.\n260\tThe remaining observed packets form the adaptation pool,\n261\tA = O \\ H. Thus, in the non-causal setting, the three sets\n262\tL, H, and A are disjoint, and L ∪ H ∪ A = {1, . . . , T }.\n263\t\n264\t3\n265\t\n266\tDuring adaptation, the pool A is further split into synthetic\n267\tmasking folds. For fold k, we choose a synthetic target set\n268\tCk ⊂ A, and define the corresponding context set Dk = A\\Ck .\n269\tFor every fold, the sets L, H, Ck , and Dk are pairwise disjoint,\n270\tand their union is the complete packet index set. The packets\n271\tin Ck are synthetically hidden and used as self-supervised\n272\ttraining targets. The packets in Dk remain available as context.\n273\tThe held-out packets in H are also masked during training, but\n274\tthey are not used in the training loss.\n275\tFor any packet index set Z ⊆ {1, . . . , T }, we define the\n276\tmasking operator\n277\t(\n278\t0, t ∈ Z,\n279\t(3)\n280\tMZ (xt ) =\n281\txt , t ∈\n282\t/ Z.\n283\tThe training objective for fold k is\n284\t\u0011\n285\tX \u0010 \u0010 (k) \u0011\n286\t(k)\n287\tLtrain (θ) =\n288\tℓ fθ ut\n289\t, xt ,\n290\t\n291\t(4)\n292\t\n293\tt∈Ck\n294\t(k)\n295\t\n296\twhere the context ut is computed from the synthetically\n297\tcorrupted waveform ML∪H∪Ck (x). The model therefore sees\n298\tthe original true losses, the held-out validation packets, and\n299\tthe current synthetic training targets as missing. The loss\n300\tis evaluated only on Ck , which contains packets that were\n301\tactually received.\n302\tFor early stopping or model selection, we evaluate the heldout objective\n303\tX\n304\tLval (θ) =\n305\tℓ(fθ (vt ) , xt ) ,\n306\t(5)\n307\tt∈H\n308\t\n309\twhere the context vt is computed from ML∪H (x). Validation\n310\ttherefore uses the same principle as training: packets in H are\n311\ttreated as synthetic losses, and their known received values\n312\tprovide the validation targets. The final adapted checkpoint\n313\tθ⋆ is selected using Lval (θ), not the true missing packets.\n314\tAfter adaptation, the model reconstructs the true packet\n315\tlosses using the received waveform with only the true losses\n316\tmasked:\n317\tx̂t = fθ⋆ (wt ),\n318\tt ∈ L,\n319\t(6)\n320\twhere the context wt is computed from ML (x). Algorithm 1\n321\tsummarizes the non-causal procedure.\n322\tB. Causal test-time tuning\n323\tIn the causal setting, audio is emitted as it arrives and\n324\talready-emitted samples are never revised. The adaptation\n325\tprocess must therefore satisfy two constraints. First, the output\n326\tat time t may depend only on packets received before or at\n327\tt. Second, any parameter update performed after time t may\n328\taffect only future outputs.\n329\tA causal update can be applied whenever an observed\n330\tpacket arrives:\n331\tθt+1 = θt − η∇θ ℓ(fθt (ut ), xt ) ,\n332\t\n333\tt ∈ O.\n334\t\n335\t(7)\n336\t\n337\tNo loss is applied for t ∈ L, since the clean packet is\n338\tunavailable. However, single-packet updates are not always\n339\tsufficient for PLC. In bursty packet loss, the model may\n340\tadvance through several consecutive missing packets while\n341\t\n342\t\f4\n343\t\n344\tIEEE/ACM TRANSACTIONS ON AUDIO, SPEECH, AND LANGUAGE PROCESSING\n345\t\n346\tAlgorithm 1 TTT-PLC non-causal test-time tuning\n347\tRequire: Test packets x1:T , loss mask m1:T , pretrained\n348\tweights θ0\n349\t1: Define true losses L = {t : mt = 1} and observed packets\n350\tO = {t : mt = 0}\n351\t2: Sample held-out set H ⊂ O and set A = O \\ H\n352\t3: Initialize θ ← θ0\n353\t4: for epoch = 1, . . . , E do\n354\t5:\n355\tForm synthetic masking folds over A\n356\t6:\n357\tfor each fold k do\n358\t7:\n359\tChoose target set Ck ⊂ A and context set Dk =\n360\tA \\ Ck\n361\t8:\n362\tMask L ∪ H ∪ Ck\n363\t9:\n364\tUpdate θ using targets in Ck\n365\t10:\n366\tend for\n367\t11:\n368\tCompute Lval (θ) on H and keep the best checkpoint\n369\tθ⋆\n370\t12: end for\n371\t13: Reconstruct the true losses t ∈ L using θ ⋆\n372\t\n373\tfeeding its own predictions back into the future context. A\n374\tsynthetic single-packet mask does not reproduce this inference\n375\tcondition.\n376\tFor recurrent PLC models such as FRN, we therefore use\n377\tburst-aware replay. Instead of masking only one observed\n378\tpacket, a training step masks a short run of observed packets, rolls the model through the entire synthetic burst, and\n379\tbackpropagates through the multi-step prediction trajectory.\n380\tThis makes the self-supervised training condition closer to the\n381\tactual burst-concealment condition encountered at inference.\n382\tTo preserve causality, burst-aware training is performed\n383\tonly on completed blocks. Let S denote the block size. The\n384\treceiver first streams a block of S packets using the current\n385\tmodel parameters. Received packets are passed through, lost\n386\tpackets are concealed, and the emitted samples are fixed.\n387\tAfter the block has ended, the model performs one or more\n388\treplay epochs using only the packets and loss mask from that\n389\tcompleted block. The updated parameters are then used for\n390\tthe next block. Because training on a block occurs only after\n391\tthat block has already been emitted, replay cannot change past\n392\toutputs and cannot use future packets. Algorithm 2 gives the\n393\tcausal block-replay procedure.\n394\tC. Streaming PARCnet test-time tuning\n395\tPARCnet requires one additional detail beyond the general\n396\tmasking construction above because its native prediction target\n397\textends beyond the packet being concealed. Let D = 320 be\n398\tthe packet length and let R = 80 be the prediction tail used\n399\tfor cross-fading. For packet t, PARCnet predicts a window of\n400\tP = D + R = 400.\n401\t\n402\t(8)\n403\t\n404\tWe denote the corresponding target window by zt ∈ RP ,\n405\tthe model prediction by ẑt = fθ (ut ), and the packet index\n406\tcontaining sample j of this window by p(t, j).\n407\tFor PARCnet, we use a streaming every-packet adaptation\n408\tprocedure. Before adaptation, the observed packets are split\n409\t\n410\tAlgorithm 2 Causal block replay\n411\tRequire: Streamed packets x1:T , loss mask m1:T , pretrained\n412\tweights θ0 , block size S\n413\t1: Initialize live weights θ ← θ0 and EMA weights θ̄ ← θ0\n414\t2: for each block do\n415\t3:\n416\tStream the next S packets with weights θ̄\n417\t4:\n418\tPass through received packets and conceal lost packets\n419\t5:\n420\tStore the completed block and its received/lost mask\n421\t6:\n422\tForm self-supervised targets by synthetically masking\n423\treceived packets inside the completed block\n424\t7:\n425\tfor replay epoch = 1, . . . , E do\n426\t8:\n427\tRoll through burst-masked received packets and\n428\tupdate θ using the native PLC loss\n429\t9:\n430\tUpdate θ̄ ← ρθ̄ + (1 − ρ)θ\n431\t10:\n432\tend for\n433\t11:\n434\tUse θ̄ only for future blocks; already emitted samples\n435\tare unchanged\n436\t12: end for\n437\tinto the training set A = O \\ H and the held-out validation\n438\tset H. The stream buffer is initialized with the lossy signal:\n439\treceived packets contain their observed samples, and true lost\n440\tpackets are zero-filled until they are concealed. The model then\n441\tscans the waveform once from left to right. If t ∈ L, the packet\n442\tis a true loss; PARCnet conceals it, writes the prediction into\n443\tthe running buffer, and takes no gradient step. If t ∈ A, the\n444\tpacket was received and is used for self-supervised adaptation:\n445\twe mask it from the neural input, predict it using the current\n446\trunning buffer, and update the model using the native PARCnet\n447\tloss. If t ∈ H, the packet remains available in the stream buffer\n448\tas received audio, but it is never used as a training target.\n449\tThe PARCnet loss is the released training objective,\n450\tℓPARC = 100 ℓqMSE + 0.5 ℓqMR-STFT ,\n451\t\n452\t(9)\n453\t\n454\twhere both terms are computed with a sample-level loss mask\n455\tq, and the squared-error term is normalized per packet. The\n456\tsample mask is essential because the 400-sample prediction\n457\twindow includes an 80-sample tail that can overlap the next\n458\tpacket. If that next packet is a true loss, those samples are\n459\tnot available to the decoder and must not contribute to the\n460\tadaptation loss. For a training packet t ∈ A, we therefore use\n461\ttr\n462\tqt,j\n463\t= I{p(t, j) ∈ A},\n464\t\n465\tj = 1, . . . , P.\n466\t\n467\t(10)\n468\t\n469\tThus, only samples that belong to packets used for training\n470\tcontribute to the loss. Samples from true losses L and held-out\n471\tvalidation packets H have zero weight in the training objective,\n472\teven if they appear inside the prediction tail.\n473\tEvery fixed number of updates, we evaluate the current\n474\tweights on the held-out packets. For validation, packets in\n475\tH are synthetically concealed and scored against their known\n476\treceived samples using the packet NMSE used in the PARCnet\n477\tevaluation protocol. The validation mask is\n478\tval\n479\tqt,j\n480\t= I{p(t, j) ∈ H},\n481\t\n482\tt ∈ H,\n483\t\n484\tj = 1, . . . , P,\n485\t\n486\t(11)\n487\t\n488\tand the validation score for a snapshot θs is\n489\t2\n490\t\n491\tV (θs ) =\n492\t\n493\tqval\n494\t1 X\n495\tt ⊙ (ẑt − zt ) 2\n496\t10 log10\n497\t.\n498\t2\n499\t|H|\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "e3f12ddc-4106-4f48-8a58-5c7df4d279a9", "uuid": "df867ca2-3a60-4acf-8650-d19f282dcc1e", "timestamp": "2026-07-06T14:15:11.620Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/ttt-plc/paper.txt", "content": "burst-aware adaptation on completed blocks and applies the\n\n\f2\n\nIEEE/ACM TRANSACTIONS ON AUDIO, SPEECH, AND LANGUAGE PROCESSING\n\nupdated model only to future audio. For music PLC, we study\nwhether a model trained for one signal class can adapt on the\ncurrent file when the test signal is in domain or out of domain.\nWe use streaming every-packet adaptation with held-out snapshot selection, so the model is updated from received packets\nwhile the deployed checkpoint is chosen without access to\nthe true losses. We evaluate the approach across speech and\nmusic backbones, non-causal and causal deployment settings,\nin-domain and out-of-domain signals, ablations, and runtime\nmeasurements. The code and experiment scripts are available\npublicly. 1\nII. R ELATED W ORK\nPacket loss concealment (PLC) is the receiver-side task\nof reconstructing missing audio packets from the packets\nthat arrived. Classical PLC methods were designed for lowcomplexity, low-latency communication systems. The G.711\nAppendix I standard [1] uses waveform substitution and attenuation to conceal short erasures. Linear-prediction methods\nsuch as Gunduzhan and Momtahan [7] estimate the missing\nwaveform from the recent past, while waveform extrapolation\nand overlap-add approaches such as Chen [8] exploit local\ntemporal continuity. Modern codecs also include packet-loss\nrobustness internally; Opus [2] combines linear prediction,\ntransform coding, and concealment tools for interactive speech\nand audio. These signal-processing methods remain attractive\nbecause of their speed and stability, but their behavior is\nfixed by design and cannot specialize to a particular speaker,\ninstrument, recording, or loss pattern at deployment time.\nDeep PLC methods learn a data-driven prior for missing\naudio. Early neural approaches formulated PLC as futureframe prediction or regression from local context. Lin et al. [9]\nuse convolutional and recurrent networks for time-domain\nreconstruction, and Westhausen and Meyer [10] developed a\ntime-domain PLC model, tPLCnet, that uses recurrent neural networks to predict missing waveform samples from a\nshort causal context. Generative approaches have also been\nexplored: Pascual et al. [11] use adversarial auto-encoding for\npacket-loss recovery, and Wang et al. [12] propose a temporalspectral GAN to synthesize plausible missing regions. Nguyen\net al. [5] introduced FRN, which performs full-band blind\nspeech PLC with a recurrent frequency-domain model, avoiding the need for an explicit loss mask at inference. For\nnetworked music, PARCnet [6] combines a classical autoregressive predictor with a neural residual branch to meet lowlatency musical constraints. Recent diffusion and flow-based\nPLC methods, such as Diff-PLC [13] and Flow-PLC [14],\nfurther improve the expressiveness of neural concealment by\nmodeling richer conditional reconstruction distributions. These\nmethods differ in architecture and training objective, but they\nare usually used as fixed pretrained systems at test time.\nPLC evaluation has also become more standardized. The\nINTERSPEECH 2022 Audio Deep PLC Challenge [3] introduced a public benchmark with realistic loss traces collected\nfrom communication scenarios, and the ICASSP 2024 Audio\nDeep PLC Challenge [15] continued this line of evaluation.\n1 https://github.com/MLSpeech/TTT-PLC\n\nPLCMOS [4] provides a learned perceptual metric targeted\nspecifically at PLC artifacts, complementing traditional intrusive metrics such as PESQ [16] and STOI [17]. Controlled\nexperiments often use bursty loss models such as Gilbert–\nElliott [18] to approximate clustered packet drops. These\nbenchmarks and metrics are important for test-time adaptation because the amount of useful received signal, the burst\nstructure, and the local loss density can all affect whether\nadaptation helps or hurts. Several recent works connect PLC\nwith automatic speech recognition. Yang and Chang [19]\nuse an ASR-oriented auxiliary loss to guide PLC toward\nreconstructions that preserve recognition-relevant information.\nZhang et al. [20] introduce semantic awareness into PLC,\nusing linguistic context to improve reconstruction during long\npacket-loss bursts. Dissen et al. [21], [22] focused on PLC for\nimproving ASR by training a front-end PLC network guided\nby a frozen ASR model.\nSelf-supervised learning provides a way to train models\nfrom structure available in the input rather than from manual\nlabels. Noise2Void [23] and Noise2Self [24] show that denoisers can be trained by predicting held-out observations from\ntheir context. Test-time adaptation updates model parameters\nduring inference to better match the current input distribution.\nTent [25] adapts image classifiers by minimizing prediction\nentropy on unlabeled test data. Related approaches in speech\nuse unlabeled objectives for zero-shot denoising or dereverberation [26]. In our setting, the unlabeled test input has a special\nstructure: some packets are missing and cannot be used for loss\ncomputation, while other packets are received and can be used\nto define a self-supervised concealment task. This differs from\nstandard test-time adaptation, where the input is usually fully\nobserved but unlabeled. It also creates different deployment\nconstraints: in the causal setting, adaptation may use only past\nreceived audio and must not revise already-emitted samples.\nDeep Image Prior [27] demonstrates that an untrained\nconvolutional network can regularize inverse problems when\noptimized to fit the observed pixels of a single corrupted image. Deep Decoder [28] shows that compact untrained neural\narchitectures can act as image priors. NeRF [29] optimizes a\nneural radiance field to fit the observations of a single scene,\nshowing the potential of per-instance neural fitting. In inverse\nproblems, ZS-SSL [30] partitions acquired MRI measurements\ninto disjoint subsets for self-supervised reconstruction without\nfully sampled reference data. Our approach follows the perinstance optimization philosophy but differs from these methods in two ways: it starts from a pretrained PLC model rather\nthan fitting a new representation from scratch, and it trains on\na proxy concealment task constructed from received packets\nwhile evaluating on the true packet losses.\nIII. M ETHOD\nThis study proposes a test-time adaptation framework for\npacket loss concealment that improves pretrained PLC models\nwithout changing their architectures or using additional training data. As described earlier, most neural PLC systems are\ndeployed as fixed models: a corrupted audio stream is passed\nthrough the pretrained concealer, and the model parameters\n\n\fDISSEN AND KESHET: TEST-TIME TUNING FOR PACKET LOSS CONCEALMENT\n\nremain unchanged for every call, recording, or packet-loss\npattern. This is limiting because the received portions of the\ntest signal contain information about the speaker, instrument,\nchannel, and local temporal structure of the current file.\nHere, we use that information directly by constructing a selfsupervised PLC task from the packets that were successfully\nreceived. Specifically, we synthetically mask a subset of the\navailable packets, train the model to reconstruct them using\nits native PLC objective, and then use the adapted model to\nconceal the true packet losses.\nWe start by presenting the notation and general setting. We\nuse the term packet to denote the unit on which the loss\nmask is defined. For the FRN model [5] this unit is an STFT\nframe, whereas for the PARCnet model [6] this unit is a 10 ms\nwaveform packet. Let x1:T = (x1 , . . . , xT ) denote the clean\npacket sequence, where xt ∈ RN , and let m1:T ∈ {0, 1}T\ndenote the packet-loss mask. We use mt = 1 for a true packet\nloss and mt = 0 for a packet that arrived at the receiver.\nThis defines two disjoint sets. The first set is the set of speech\nframes which are originally lost and is denoted L. The second\nset is the set of the observed frames, denoted by O. That is\nL = {t : mt = 1},\nO = {t : mt = 0},\n\n(1)\n\nwhere L ∩ O = ∅ and L ∪ O = {1, . . . , T }. The clean packet\nxt is available to the receiver only for t ∈ O. Frames (or\npackets) in L are used only for final evaluation and are never\nused as adaptation targets.\nLet fθ be a pretrained PLC model with parameters θ. Given\nthe context available at frame or packet index t, denoted by\nut , the model predicts the lost packet xt\nx̂t = fθ (ut ).\n\n(2)\n\nNote that is the packet at time t is observed the model should\nreturn it as is. The context ut depends on the backbone. It\nmay contain past waveform samples, STFT frames, recurrent\nstates, an autoregressive buffer, or a combination of these. Let\nℓ(x̂t , xt ) denote the native PLC loss used to train and find the\nparameters θ of the pretrained model fθ .\nThe proposed method creates a self-supervised PLC task\nfrom the observed packets. We choose subsets of O, mask\nthem synthetically, and train the model to reconstruct them.\nThe true lost packets L remain masked during adaptation and\nare not used in the loss.\nA. Non-causal test-time tuning\nIn the non-causal setting, the complete received file is\navailable before final reconstruction. We adapt a separate copy\nof the pretrained model for each test file and reset the model\nto the public checkpoint before moving to the next file.\nWe first partition the observed packets into a held-out\nvalidation set and an adaptation pool. Specifically, we sample\na held-out set H ⊂ O, where H contains packets that\narrived at the receiver but are not used for gradient updates.\nThe remaining observed packets form the adaptation pool,\nA = O \\ H. Thus, in the non-causal setting, the three sets\nL, H, and A are disjoint, and L ∪ H ∪ A = {1, . . . , T }.\n\n3\n\nDuring adaptation, the pool A is further split into synthetic\nmasking folds. For fold k, we choose a synthetic target set\nCk ⊂ A, and define the corresponding context set Dk = A\\Ck .\nFor every fold, the sets L, H, Ck , and Dk are pairwise disjoint,\nand their union is the complete packet index set. The packets\nin Ck are synthetically hidden and used as self-supervised\ntraining targets. The packets in Dk remain available as context.\nThe held-out packets in H are also masked during training, but\nthey are not used in the training loss.\nFor any packet index set Z ⊆ {1, . . . , T }, we define the\nmasking operator\n(\n0, t ∈ Z,\n(3)\nMZ (xt ) =\nxt , t ∈\n/ Z.\nThe training objective for fold k is\n\u0011\nX \u0010 \u0010 (k) \u0011\n(k)\nLtrain (θ) =\nℓ fθ ut\n, xt ,\n\n(4)\n\nt∈Ck\n(k)\n\nwhere the context ut is computed from the synthetically\ncorrupted waveform ML∪H∪Ck (x). The model therefore sees\nthe original true losses, the held-out validation packets, and\nthe current synthetic training targets as missing. The loss\nis evaluated only on Ck , which contains packets that were\nactually received.\nFor early stopping or model selection, we evaluate the heldout objective\nX\nLval (θ) =\nℓ(fθ (vt ) , xt ) ,\n(5)\nt∈H\n\nwhere the context vt is computed from ML∪H (x). Validation\ntherefore uses the same principle as training: packets in H are\ntreated as synthetic losses, and their known received values\nprovide the validation targets. The final adapted checkpoint\nθ⋆ is selected using Lval (θ), not the true missing packets.\nAfter adaptation, the model reconstructs the true packet\nlosses using the received waveform with only the true losses\nmasked:\nx̂t = fθ⋆ (wt ),\nt ∈ L,\n(6)\nwhere the context wt is computed from ML (x). Algorithm 1\nsummarizes the non-causal procedure.\nB. Causal test-time tuning\nIn the causal setting, audio is emitted as it arrives and\nalready-emitted samples are never revised. The adaptation\nprocess must therefore satisfy two constraints. First, the output\nat time t may depend only on packets received before or at\nt. Second, any parameter update performed after time t may\naffect only future outputs.\nA causal update can be applied whenever an observed\npacket arrives:\nθt+1 = θt − η∇θ ℓ(fθt (ut ), xt ) ,\n\nt ∈ O.\n\n(7)\n\nNo loss is applied for t ∈ L, since the clean packet is\nunavailable. However, single-packet updates are not always\nsufficient for PLC. In bursty packet loss, the model may\nadvance through several consecutive missing packets while\n\n\f4\n\nIEEE/ACM TRANSACTIONS ON AUDIO, SPEECH, AND LANGUAGE PROCESSING\n\nAlgorithm 1 TTT-PLC non-causal test-time tuning\nRequire: Test packets x1:T , loss mask m1:T , pretrained\nweights θ0\n1: Define true losses L = {t : mt = 1} and observed packets\nO = {t : mt = 0}\n2: Sample held-out set H ⊂ O and set A = O \\ H\n3: Initialize θ ← θ0\n4: for epoch = 1, . . . , E do\n5:\nForm synthetic masking folds over A\n6:\nfor each fold k do\n7:\nChoose target set Ck ⊂ A and context set Dk =\nA \\ Ck\n8:\nMask L ∪ H ∪ Ck\n9:\nUpdate θ using targets in Ck\n10:\nend for\n11:\nCompute Lval (θ) on H and keep the best checkpoint\nθ⋆\n12: end for\n13: Reconstruct the true losses t ∈ L using θ ⋆\n\nfeeding its own predictions back into the future context. A\nsynthetic single-packet mask does not reproduce this inference\ncondition.\nFor recurrent PLC models such as FRN, we therefore use\nburst-aware replay. Instead of masking only one observed\npacket, a training step masks a short run of observed packets, rolls the model through the entire synthetic burst, and\nbackpropagates through the multi-step prediction trajectory.\nThis makes the self-supervised training condition closer to the\nactual burst-concealment condition encountered at inference.\nTo preserve causality, burst-aware training is performed\nonly on completed blocks. Let S denote the block size. The\nreceiver first streams a block of S packets using the current\nmodel parameters. Received packets are passed through, lost\npackets are concealed, and the emitted samples are fixed.\nAfter the block has ended, the model performs one or more\nreplay epochs using only the packets and loss mask from that\ncompleted block. The updated parameters are then used for\nthe next block. Because training on a block occurs only after\nthat block has already been emitted, replay cannot change past\noutputs and cannot use future packets. Algorithm 2 gives the\ncausal block-replay procedure.\nC. Streaming PARCnet test-time tuning\nPARCnet requires one additional detail beyond the general\nmasking construction above because its native prediction target\nextends beyond the packet being concealed. Let D = 320 be\nthe packet length and let R = 80 be the prediction tail used\nfor cross-fading. For packet t, PARCnet predicts a window of\nP = D + R = 400.\n\n(8)\n\nWe denote the corresponding target window by zt ∈ RP ,\nthe model prediction by ẑt = fθ (ut ), and the packet index\ncontaining sample j of this window by p(t, j).\nFor PARCnet, we use a streaming every-packet adaptation\nprocedure. Before adaptation, the observed packets are split\n\nAlgorithm 2 Causal block replay\nRequire: Streamed packets x1:T , loss mask m1:T , pretrained\nweights θ0 , block size S\n1: Initialize live weights θ ← θ0 and EMA weights θ̄ ← θ0\n2: for each block do\n3:\nStream the next S packets with weights θ̄\n4:\nPass through received packets and conceal lost packets\n5:\nStore the completed block and its received/lost mask\n6:\nForm self-supervised targets by synthetically masking\nreceived packets inside the completed block\n7:\nfor replay epoch = 1, . . . , E do\n8:\nRoll through burst-masked received packets and\nupdate θ using the native PLC loss\n9:\nUpdate θ̄ ← ρθ̄ + (1 − ρ)θ\n10:\nend for\n11:\nUse θ̄ only for future blocks; already emitted samples\nare unchanged\n12: end for\ninto the training set A = O \\ H and the held-out validation\nset H. The stream buffer is initialized with the lossy signal:\nreceived packets contain their observed samples, and true lost\npackets are zero-filled until they are concealed. The model then\nscans the waveform once from left to right. If t ∈ L, the packet\nis a true loss; PARCnet conceals it, writes the prediction into\nthe running buffer, and takes no gradient step. If t ∈ A, the\npacket was received and is used for self-supervised adaptation:\nwe mask it from the neural input, predict it using the current\nrunning buffer, and update the model using the native PARCnet\nloss. If t ∈ H, the packet remains available in the stream buffer\nas received audio, but it is never used as a training target.\nThe PARCnet loss is the released training objective,\nℓPARC = 100 ℓqMSE + 0.5 ℓqMR-STFT ,\n\n(9)\n\nwhere both terms are computed with a sample-level loss mask\nq, and the squared-error term is normalized per packet. The\nsample mask is essential because the 400-sample prediction\nwindow includes an 80-sample tail that can overlap the next\npacket. If that next packet is a true loss, those samples are\nnot available to the decoder and must not contribute to the\nadaptation loss. For a training packet t ∈ A, we therefore use\ntr\nqt,j\n= I{p(t, j) ∈ A},\n\nj = 1, . . . , P.\n\n(10)\n\nThus, only samples that belong to packets used for training\ncontribute to the loss. Samples from true losses L and held-out\nvalidation packets H have zero weight in the training objective,\neven if they appear inside the prediction tail.\nEvery fixed number of updates, we evaluate the current\nweights on the held-out packets. For validation, packets in\nH are synthetically concealed and scored against their known\nreceived samples using the packet NMSE used in the PARCnet\nevaluation protocol. The validation mask is\nval\nqt,j\n= I{p(t, j) ∈ H},\n\nt ∈ H,\n\nj = 1, . . . , P,\n\n(11)\n\nand the validation score for a snapshot θs is\n2\n\nV (θs ) =\n\nqval\n1 X\nt ⊙ (ẑt − zt ) 2\n10 log10\n.\n2\n|H|", "numLines": 400, "startLine": 100, "totalLines": 1534}}}
