{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a547dcbfe89f6909", "type": "tool_result", "content": "500\tqval\n501\tt ⊙ zt 2\n502\tt∈H\n503\t\n504\t(12)\n505\t\n506\t\fDISSEN AND KESHET: TEST-TIME TUNING FOR PACKET LOSS CONCEALMENT\n507\t\n508\tAlgorithm 3 PARCnet streaming adaptation with held-out\n509\tsnapshot selection\n510\tRequire: Lossy packets, loss mask m1:T , pretrained weights\n511\tθ0 , held-out set H, snapshot cadence C\n512\t1: Define L = {t : mt = 1}, O = {t : mt = 0}, and\n513\tA=O\\H\n514\t2: Initialize θ ← θ0 , initialize the running buffer with\n515\treceived packets and zeros at true losses\n516\t3: Set V ⋆ ← ∞ and θ ⋆ ← θ0\n517\t4: for t = 1, . . . , T do\n518\t5:\n519\tif t ∈ L then\n520\t6:\n521\tConceal packet t, write the prediction into the\n522\trunning buffer, and take no gradient step\n523\t7:\n524\telse if t ∈ A then\n525\t8:\n526\tSynthetically mask packet t from the neural input\n527\t9:\n528\tPredict ẑt = fθ (ut ) using the current running\n529\tbuffer\n530\t10:\n531\tUpdate θ using ℓPARC with training mask qtr\n532\tt\n533\t11:\n534\telse\n535\t12:\n536\tPass through held-out packet t and take no gradient\n537\tstep\n538\t13:\n539\tend if\n540\t14:\n541\tif C gradient updates have occurred since the last\n542\tsnapshot then\n543\t15:\n544\tCompute V (θ) by synthetically concealing H\n545\t16:\n546\tif V (θ) < V ⋆ then\n547\t17:\n548\tSet V ⋆ ← V (θ) and θ⋆ ← θ\n549\t18:\n550\tend if\n551\t19:\n552\tend if\n553\t20: end for\n554\t21: For two-pass deployment, reconstruct the true losses L\n555\tusing the selected checkpoint θ⋆\n556\t\n557\tThe deployed checkpoint is selected by\n558\tθ⋆ = θs⋆ ,\n559\t\n560\ts⋆ = arg min V (θs ).\n561\t\n562\t(13)\n563\t\n564\ts\n565\t\n566\tThe true lost packets L are excluded from both training and\n567\tvalidation; they are used only for final evaluation. Algorithm 3\n568\tsummarizes the procedure.\n569\tIV. E VALUATION S ETTINGS\n570\tThis section describes the pretrained backbones, datasets,\n571\tpacket-loss conditions, metrics, and implementation details\n572\tused in the experiments. In all experiments, adaptation is\n573\tperformed independently for each test waveform. The model\n574\tis reset to the released public checkpoint before processing\n575\tthe next waveform, so no information is transferred across\n576\tevaluation utterances or recordings.\n577\tA. Backbones\n578\tWe evaluate TTT-PLC on two open-source PLC backbones.\n579\tThe first is FRN [5], a full-band recurrent speech PLC model\n580\tthat operates on STFT frames at 48 kHz. FRN processes the\n581\tsignal frame by frame while maintaining recurrent state, and\n582\tavailable frames are passed through in the STFT domain. Only\n583\t\n584\t5\n585\t\n586\tframes marked as lost are replaced by the model prediction.\n587\tFor FRN, we continue training with the released spectral\n588\tobjective and evaluate both the non-causal adaptation procedure in Algorithm 1 and the causal block-replay procedure in\n589\tAlgorithm 2.\n590\tThe second backbone is PARCnet [6], a hybrid\n591\tautoregressive-neural PLC model designed for real-time\n592\tnetworked music. We use the released PARCnet checkpoint\n593\tand retain the original AR-plus-neural architecture. Audio\n594\tis mono at 32 kHz, each packet contains D = 320\n595\tsamples, corresponding to 10 ms, and the model predicts a\n596\tD + 80 = 400-sample window so that the final 80 samples\n597\tcan be cross-faded against the subsequent buffer. The frozen\n598\tPARCnet system combines a 10-packet AR context with\n599\ta 7-packet neural residual context. The neural residual is\n600\tfaded in over 16 samples, and the combined AR-plus-neural\n601\tprediction is faded out over the 80-sample tail. Available\n602\tpackets are passed through unchanged, and only packets\n603\tindicated as lost by the trace are reconstructed.\n604\tB. Datasets\n605\tWe use separate speech and music evaluation settings to test\n606\tlong-file adaptation, short-file speech PLC, in-domain music\n607\tbehavior, and out-of-domain adaptation.\n608\tLibriSpeech-40. LibriSpeech test-clean [31] is used\n609\tto test whether adaptation can accumulate over long speech\n610\trecordings. We concatenate utterances by speaker to form 40\n611\tapproximately 8-minute files at 48 kHz. This setting is intentionally long: it exposes whether causal adaptation improves\n612\tafter several received blocks and whether the adapted model\n613\tdrifts later in the file. The same 40-speaker set is also used as\n614\tthe out-of-domain speech condition for PARCnet.\n615\tPLC Challenge 2022 speech. The PLC Challenge 2022 test\n616\tset contains 966 short blind-test files at 16 kHz with real\n617\tpacket-loss traces from Microsoft Teams calls [3]. We use this\n618\tbenchmark because it is a standard speech PLC evaluation set\n619\tand because the files are short, which stresses the low-latency\n620\tsetting where a causal replay method has limited time to adapt.\n621\tPARCnet in-domain music. The in-domain music condition\n622\tuses the MAESTRO recording used in the PARCnet paper [6],\n623\t[32]. We evaluate the full 50-minute file, a 5-minute crop, and\n624\tfive 30-second chunks at 32 kHz. PARCnet was trained on\n625\tmusic data and is already well matched to this audio. This\n626\tcondition tests whether test-time tuning can avoid harmful\n627\tover-adaptation when the frozen model is already close to the\n628\ttarget signal distribution.\n629\tPARCnet out-of-domain speech. To evaluate adaptation under distribution shift, we apply PARCnet to LibriSpeech-40\n630\tusing the same 32 kHz packet-loss interface. This setting is\n631\tdeliberately out of domain for PARCnet and tests whether\n632\tself-supervised adaptation from received packets can move a\n633\tmusic-trained PLC model toward a new signal class without\n634\texternal data.\n635\tC. Packet-loss conditions\n636\tFor the LibriSpeech-40, FRN experiments, loss masks are\n637\ttiled from PLC Challenge 2022 traces. The selected masks\n638\t\n639\t\f6\n640\t\n641\tIEEE/ACM TRANSACTIONS ON AUDIO, SPEECH, AND LANGUAGE PROCESSING\n642\t\n643\tspan loss rates from 0% to 70.5% and contain bursts from 1\n644\tto 28 frames. For the PLC Challenge 2022 evaluation, we use\n645\tthe official packet-loss traces as provided with the benchmark.\n646\tThese traces are used without modification.\n647\tFor the PARCnet experiments, we use nominal packet-loss\n648\trates of 10%, 20%, and 30%. Traces are generated once\n649\tfor each file and loss rate using a fixed seed. The true lost\n650\tpackets are known as loss locations, but their clean samples\n651\tare excluded from training and validation and are used only\n652\tfor final evaluation. The PARCnet evaluation grid contains 141\n653\tfile-rate cells: 40 LibriSpeech speakers times three loss rates,\n654\tthe 50-minute MAESTRO file times three loss rates, the 5minute MAESTRO crop times three loss rates, and five 30second MAESTRO chunks times three loss rates.\n655\tD. Metrics and aggregation\n656\tFor FRN, we follow the evaluation protocol of the original\n657\tFRN study and report STOI [17], wideband PESQ [16], logspectral distance (LSD), intrusive PLCMOS, and non-intrusive\n658\tPLCMOS [4]. PESQ and PLCMOS are evaluated at 16 kHz.\n659\tSTOI and LSD are computed at the native sampling rate of\n660\teach corpus. On LibriSpeech-40, all five metrics are computed\n661\ton non-overlapping 20-second windows. The window scores\n662\tare first averaged within each file and then averaged across\n663\tthe 40 speakers. The 20-second windowing avoids PLCMOS\n664\tlength limits and keeps the metric protocol consistent across\n665\tall five metrics. On PLC Challenge 2022, the files are short\n666\tenough to evaluate as complete files.\n667\tFor PARCnet, we follow the objective evaluation protocol\n668\tused in the original PARCnet study. The primary reconstruction metric is packet NMSE in dB, computed over true lost\n669\tpackets as\n670\tNMSEpkt = 10 log10\n671\t\n672\t∥y − ŷ∥22\n673\t,\n674\t∥y∥22\n675\t\n676\t(14)\n677\t\n678\twhere y is the ground-truth lost packet and ŷ is the reconstructed packet. Lower NMSE is better. We also report\n679\tMel spectral convergence (Mel-SC) [33], which measures\n680\tspectral error after applying a Mel-frequency filterbank to the\n681\tmagnitude STFT. Following PARCnet, Mel-SC is computed\n682\tusing 64 triangular Mel filters and a 512-sample Hann window with 50% overlap at the native 32 kHz sampling rate.\n683\tTo include perceptual measures, we report PEAQ [34] and\n684\tPLCMOS [4]. PEAQ is reported as Objective Difference Grade\n685\t(ODG), averaged over non-overlapping 10-second windows\n686\tafter resampling to 48 kHz. PLCMOS is the non-intrusive\n687\tPLCMOS score, averaged over non-overlapping 10-second\n688\twindows after resampling to 16 kHz. We also track the\n689\tsilence-energy ratio as a diagnostic guardrail for silence-fill\n690\tartifacts. When confidence intervals are reported, they are 95%\n691\tbootstrap intervals over per-file deltas.\n692\tE. Implementation details\n693\tFor FRN, the non-causal setting uses the full received file\n694\tbefore final reconstruction and provides a per-file adaptation\n695\tceiling. The causal setting uses block replay. In this setting, the\n696\tmodel streams a block with the current parameters, emits the\n697\t\n698\tcorresponding audio, and then trains only on that completed\n699\tblock. Updated weights affect only future blocks.\n700\tFor LibriSpeech-40, causal FRN uses blocks of 3000\n701\tframes, corresponding to 30-seconds, after a 1000-frame\n702\twarmup. For PLC Challenge 2022, causal FRN uses blocks of\n703\t200 frames after a 200-frame warmup, matching the shorter\n704\tfile duration. In both datasets, replay uses six epochs per block,\n705\ta 128-frame loss history, AdamW with learning rate 5 × 10−6 ,\n706\tweight decay 10−6 , gradient clipping at L2 norm 2.0, and an\n707\tL2 pull of strength 5 × 10−7 on the joiner parameters. The\n708\tburst depth is anchored to observed packet losses,\n709\tKburst = min (12, max (4, Kobs )) ,\n710\t\n711\t(15)\n712\t\n713\twhere Kobs is the longest of the last ten completed real bursts.\n714\tWe maintain exponential moving average (EMA) weights with\n715\tcoefficient 0.99 and use this smoothed copy of the adapted\n716\tmodel for streaming output.\n717\tFor PARCnet, the proposed method is streaming everypacket TTT with held-out snapshot selection. We use AdamW\n718\twith learning rate 5×10−6 , weight decay 10−4 , one update per\n719\tavailable training packet, gradient clipping at L2 norm 2.0, and\n720\tthe released PARCnet loss 100 · MSE + 0.5 · MR-STFT with\n721\tper-packet normalization. A random 10% subset of available\n722\tpackets is held out before training using seed 42. These heldout packets are never used for gradient updates; they are used\n723\tonly to select checkpoints using held-out packet NMSE. We\n724\tevaluate snapshots every C updates, with C = 400 for the 40speaker headline experiments and C = 3200 for the 50-minute\n725\tMAESTRO file. The same adaptation trajectory supports a\n726\tcausal best-val mode, which uses only snapshots validated\n727\tso far, and a two-pass best-val mode, which selects the best\n728\tsnapshot over the whole file and reconstructs the true losses\n729\tin a second pass. We also report single-pass oracle snapshot\n730\tselection as an upper bound and multi-epoch adaptation as a\n731\tquality-oriented configuration.\n732\tThe PARCnet prediction window contains the target packet\n733\tand an 80-sample tail. Because this tail can overlap a neighboring true loss, all PARCnet adaptation losses are computed\n734\twith a sample-level mask that excludes any samples belonging\n735\tto true lost packets. This mask is applied to both the MSE and\n736\tMR-STFT terms. Thus, clean audio at true loss positions is\n737\tnever used during training or validation, even when it lies\n738\tinside the prediction tail of an observed packet.\n739\tV. R ESULTS\n740\tIn this section, we evaluate our method, TTT-PLC, across\n741\tspeech and music PLC, non-causal and causal deployment\n742\tsettings, in-domain and out-of-domain signals, and multiple\n743\tpacket-loss rates. We first study FRN on long LibriSpeech\n744\trecordings and on the PLC Challenge 2022 test set to measure\n745\thow much of the non-causal adaptation gain can be recovered\n746\tunder causality. We then evaluate PARCnet on out-of-domain\n747\tspeech and in-domain music.\n748\tA. FRN: non-causal ceiling and causal replay on long files\n749\tTable I reports FRN results on LibriSpeech-40. The noncausal setting adapts using the full received file before the final\n750\t\n751\t\fDISSEN AND KESHET: TEST-TIME TUNING FOR PACKET LOSS CONCEALMENT\n752\t\n753\t7\n754\t\n755\tTABLE I\n756\tFRN RESULTS ON L IBRI S PEECH -40 LONG FILES . E NTRIES ARE ABSOLUTE SCORES ; PARENTHESES GIVE THE CHANGE FROM FROZEN AND THE NUMBER\n757\tOF IMPROVED FILES . T HE CAUSAL CONFIDENCE ROW GIVES 95% BOOTSTRAP CONFIDENCE INTERVALS FOR THE CHANGE FROM FROZEN .\n758\t\n759\tMethod\n760\tFrozen FRN\n761\tNon-causal\n762\tCausal replay\n763\tCausal 95% CI\n764\tCausal/non-causal gain\n765\t\n766\tSTOI ↑\n767\t\n768\tPESQ ↑\n769\t\n770\tLSD ↓\n771\t\n772\tPLCMOS-I ↑\n773\t\n774\tPLCMOS-NI ↑\n775\t\n776\t0.911\n777\t0.920 (+0.0092; 39/40)\n778\t0.919 (+0.0078; 39/40)\n779\t[+0.0054,+0.0104]\n780\t85%\n781\t\n782\t2.442\n783\t2.489 (+0.047; 38/40)\n784\t2.482 (+0.040; 38/40)\n785\t[+0.0313,+0.0485]\n786\t84%\n787\t\n788\t1.036\n789\t0.737 (-0.299; 39/40)\n790\t0.732 (-0.304; 39/40)\n791\t[-0.4047,-0.2153]\n792\t102%\n793\t\n794\t2.661\n795\t2.706 (+0.045; 32/40)\n796\t2.696 (+0.035; 32/40)\n797\t[+0.0164,+0.0524]\n798\t77%\n799\t\n800\t2.589\n801\t2.631 (+0.042; 31/40)\n802\t2.626 (+0.037; 30/40)\n803\t[+0.0228,+0.0518]\n804\t88%\n805\t\n806\treconstruction, and therefore serves as a per-file adaptation\n807\tceiling. Causal replay is more constrained: it emits each block\n808\tbefore replay training is performed, and updated parameters\n809\tcan affect only future blocks. Because FRN is recurrent and\n810\treal losses often occur in bursts, replay training uses short\n811\tsynthetic bursts rather than only isolated single-frame masks;\n812\twe refer to this part of the adaptation as burst-aware. Despite\n813\tthe causal restriction, causal replay recovers most of the noncausal gain. It reaches 84–85% of the non-causal improvement\n814\ton STOI and PESQ, 77–88% on the two PLCMOS heads,\n815\tand slightly exceeds the non-causal LSD gain. The bootstrap\n816\tconfidence intervals in Table I show that these gains are\n817\tconsistent across files.\n818\tFigure 1 shows how the causal gains evolve over time in the\n819\tlong LibriSpeech-40 files. During the first 30-seconds block,\n820\tthe output is identical to frozen FRN because no replay update\n821\thas occurred. After the first completed block is replayed,\n822\tthe next block immediately improves across the metrics. By\n823\troughly 60–70 seconds, the method reaches a stable plateau\n824\tand later block boundaries provide smaller refinements, with\n825\tno visible late-file drift.\n826\tB. FRN: PLC Challenge 2022 test set\n827\tTable II evaluates the same FRN adaptation idea on the 966file PLC Challenge 2022 test set. This benchmark contains\n828\tmuch shorter files than LibriSpeech-40, so the amount of\n829\tcausal adaptation time is limited. Even in this setting, causal\n830\treplay improves every metric relative to frozen FRN.\n831\tThe confidence intervals in Table II show that the improvements are stable across the 966-file test set. Together with\n832\tthe LibriSpeech-40 results, this shows that burst-aware block\n833\treplay on received packets improves FRN in both long-file and\n834\tshort-file speech PLC settings.\n835\tC. FRN runtime\n836\tTable III reports FRN timing on a representative\n837\tLibriSpeech-style file. Here, EMA denotes the exponential\n838\tmoving average weight copy used for reconstruction. The\n839\tabsolute real-time factors come from an unoptimized frameby-frame Python implementation and should be interpreted\n840\tmainly as relative costs. Causal replay has a wall-clock cost\n841\tcomparable to the six-epoch non-causal configuration because\n842\tboth perform repeated replay training. Its advantage in this\n843\timplementation is causal validity rather than lower compute:\n844\temitted samples are never revised, and each replay update\n845\taffects only future blocks.\n846\t\n847\tD. PARCnet: per-file test-time training\n848\tWe next evaluate TTT-PLC on PARCnet. The adaptation\n849\tprocedure follows the no-leak construction in Section III-C:\n850\tonly received packets are used for training and held-out\n851\tvalidation, while true lost packets are used only for final\n852\tevaluation. We use LibriSpeech-40 as an out-of-domain speech\n853\tcondition and the MAESTRO solo-piano recording from the\n854\tPARCnet evaluation as the in-domain music condition.\n855\tWe compare frozen PARCnet with three held-out-selection\n856\tvariants. Causal best-val conceals each lost packet using the\n857\tbest snapshot validated so far in the stream. Two-pass best-val\n858\tselects the best snapshot after a full adaptation pass and then\n859\treconstructs the file with that checkpoint. Multi-epoch bestval extends the same selection rule across multiple adaptation\n860\tepochs and represents the offline, quality-oriented setting. We\n861\talso report an oracle selector that chooses the best snapshot\n862\tusing the true lost packets; this is an upper bound and is not\n863\tdeployable.\n864\t1) Out-of-domain and in-domain evaluation: Table IV reports the out-of-domain LibriSpeech results. Frozen PARCnet\n865\tgives little packet-NMSE improvement relative to zero-fill,\n866\tranging from −0.06 to +0.30 dB across the three packetloss rates. Causal best-val and two-pass best-val both substantially reduce packet NMSE. Two-pass best-val reaches\n867\t−1.84, −1.76, and −1.59 dB at 10%, 20%, and 30% packet\n868\tloss, respectively, while causal best-val reaches −1.63, −1.57,\n869\tand −1.39 dB. Multi-epoch best-val gives the largest packetNMSE reductions in this condition, reaching −2.46, −2.34,\n870\tand −2.04 dB.\n871\tTable V reports the in-domain MAESTRO results on the 50minute piano file. Frozen PARCnet is already strong in this\n872\tcondition, with packet NMSE between −4.28 and −5.28 dB\n873\tacross packet-loss rates. The single-pass held-out selectors\n874\tremain close to frozen and provide modest additional packetNMSE improvements: causal best-val reaches −5.52, −5.12,\n875\tand −4.40 dB at 10%, 20%, and 30% loss, respectively, while\n876\ttwo-pass best-val reaches −5.59, −5.08, and −4.43 dB. The\n877\tsingle-pass oracle is only slightly better, indicating that heldout selection leaves little single-pass selection gain unused in\n878\tthis in-domain setting. Multi-epoch adaptation further reduces\n879\tpacket NMSE at all three loss rates, reaching −5.94, −5.49,\n880\tand −4.55 dB, although the perceptual metrics remain mixed.\n881\tThus, the MAESTRO results show that held-out adaptation can\n882\timprove packet-level reconstruction even when the frozen indomain model is already strong, with the largest gains obtained\n883\tby the offline multi-epoch setting.\n884\t\n885\t\f8\n886\t\n887\tIEEE/ACM TRANSACTIONS ON AUDIO, SPEECH, AND LANGUAGE PROCESSING\n888\t\n889\tTABLE II\n890\tFRN RESULTS ON THE 966- FILE PLC C HALLENGE 2022 TEST SET. E NTRIES ARE ABSOLUTE SCORES ; PARENTHESES GIVE THE CHANGE FROM FROZEN\n891\tAND THE WIN RATE . T HE CAUSAL CONFIDENCE ROW GIVES 95% BOOTSTRAP CONFIDENCE INTERVALS FOR THE CHANGE FROM FROZEN .\n892\t\n893\tSTOI ↑\n894\t\n895\tPESQ ↑\n896\t\n897\tLSD ↓\n898\t\n899\tPLCMOS-I ↑\n900\t\n901\tPLCMOS-NI ↑\n902\t\n903\t0.8854\n904\t0.8910 (+0.0056; 70%)\n905\t[+0.0040,+0.0078]\n906\t\n907\t2.2816\n908\t2.3706 (+0.089; 86%)\n909\t[+0.0786,+0.1001]\n910\t\n911\t2.1756\n912\t1.9776 (-0.198; 79%)\n913\t[-0.2178,-0.1782]\n914\t\n915\t2.7732\n916\t2.9092 (+0.136; 74%)\n917\t[+0.1199,+0.1529]\n918\t\n919\t2.6672\n920\t2.9352 (+0.268; 81%)\n921\t[+0.2390,+0.2966]\n922\t\n923\tMethod\n924\tFrozen FRN\n925\tCausal replay\n926\tCausal 95% CI\n927\t\n928\tTABLE III\n929\tFRN RUNTIME ON A L IBRI S PEECH - STYLE FILE , SINGLE GPU. RTF IS\n930\tCOMPUTE TIME DIVIDED BY AUDIO DURATION ; LOWER IS FASTER .\n931\tConfiguration\n932\t\n933\tRTF ↓\n934\t\n935\tRelative RT\n936\t\n937\tFrozen FRN\n938\tSingle-pass causal\n939\tNon-causal anchored, no EMA\n940\tNon-causal anchored+EMA\n941\t\n942\t0.31\n943\t0.66\n944\t4.34\n945\t4.70\n946\t\n947\t3.2×\n948\t1.5×\n949\t0.23×\n950\t0.21×\n951\t\n952\t2) Held-out snapshot selection: To evaluate the quality of\n953\theld-out model selection, we compare best-val selection with\n954\tan oracle selector that chooses, from the same single-pass\n955\tadaptation trajectory, the snapshot minimizing packet NMSE\n956\ton the true lost packets. The oracle uses clean loss-region\n957\taudio and is therefore not deployable; it is used only as an\n958\tupper bound on snapshot selection within a fixed adaptation\n959\ttrajectory. Across all 141 file-rate cells, held-out selection is\n960\twithin a mean 0.02 dB of this oracle, with median difference\n961\t0.000 dB. It selects the exact oracle snapshot in 86 of 141 cells,\n962\tand the largest observed gap is 0.41 dB. These results indicate\n963\tthat validation on held-out received packets is an accurate\n964\tproxy for selecting snapshots without using the unavailable\n965\tclean lost packets.\n966\t3) Causal algorithm deployment: The causal best-val mode\n967\tuses only snapshots that have already been validated at the\n968\ttime each lost packet is concealed. On the out-of-domain\n969\tspeech condition, it trails two-pass best-val by approximately\n970\t0.1–0.2 dB in packet NMSE, for example −1.63 versus\n971\t−1.84 dB at 10% packet loss. On the in-domain MAESTRO\n972\tfile, causal best-val remains close to both frozen and twopass best-val. Thus, most of the single-pass adaptation gain is\n973\tavailable even when future validation information is not used\n974\tto reconstruct past losses.\n975\tFigure 2 shows the position-dependent behavior on out-ofdomain LibriSpeech at r = 0.10. The causal curve starts closer\n976\tto frozen because only early snapshots have been validated,\n977\tbut it improves as more received packets become available\n978\tand approaches the two-pass curve near the end of the file.\n979\tThe two-pass and multi-epoch curves are comparatively stable\n980\tover file position because they use selected checkpoints for\n981\treconstruction over the full file, with multi-epoch providing\n982\tthe largest packet-NMSE improvement throughout.\n983\t4) Multi-epoch adaptation: Running adaptation for five\n984\tepochs and selecting the best snapshot across all epochs\n985\tgives the strongest completed PARCnet configuration when\n986\toffline adaptation time is available. On the held-out validation packets, the best snapshot across all epochs improves\n987\tmedian packet NMSE by −0.40 dB relative to the single-\n988\t\n989\tepoch best snapshot, with a 95% confidence interval of\n990\t[−0.48, −0.35] dB. The selected snapshot lies in epochs 4–5\n991\tfor approximately 95% of cells, indicating that the validation\n992\ttrajectory is still improving beyond the first pass.\n993\tThe validation improvement also transfers to the true lost\n994\tpackets in the completed multi-epoch cells. Relative to the\n995\tsingle-epoch best-val checkpoint from the same adaptation\n996\trun, the across-epoch selected checkpoint improves test packet\n997\tNMSE by about 0.5 dB on average and improves every\n998\tsetting. Table IV shows this effect on out-of-domain speech,\n999\twhere multi-epoch best-val gives lower packet NMSE than\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "e3f12ddc-4106-4f48-8a58-5c7df4d279a9", "uuid": "4d02cf64-11fc-4205-94b4-75358743c718", "timestamp": "2026-07-06T14:15:28.650Z", "tool_use_result": {"type": "text", "file": {"filePath": "/tmp/ttt-plc/paper.txt", "content": "qval\nt ⊙ zt 2\nt∈H\n\n(12)\n\n\fDISSEN AND KESHET: TEST-TIME TUNING FOR PACKET LOSS CONCEALMENT\n\nAlgorithm 3 PARCnet streaming adaptation with held-out\nsnapshot selection\nRequire: Lossy packets, loss mask m1:T , pretrained weights\nθ0 , held-out set H, snapshot cadence C\n1: Define L = {t : mt = 1}, O = {t : mt = 0}, and\nA=O\\H\n2: Initialize θ ← θ0 , initialize the running buffer with\nreceived packets and zeros at true losses\n3: Set V ⋆ ← ∞ and θ ⋆ ← θ0\n4: for t = 1, . . . , T do\n5:\nif t ∈ L then\n6:\nConceal packet t, write the prediction into the\nrunning buffer, and take no gradient step\n7:\nelse if t ∈ A then\n8:\nSynthetically mask packet t from the neural input\n9:\nPredict ẑt = fθ (ut ) using the current running\nbuffer\n10:\nUpdate θ using ℓPARC with training mask qtr\nt\n11:\nelse\n12:\nPass through held-out packet t and take no gradient\nstep\n13:\nend if\n14:\nif C gradient updates have occurred since the last\nsnapshot then\n15:\nCompute V (θ) by synthetically concealing H\n16:\nif V (θ) < V ⋆ then\n17:\nSet V ⋆ ← V (θ) and θ⋆ ← θ\n18:\nend if\n19:\nend if\n20: end for\n21: For two-pass deployment, reconstruct the true losses L\nusing the selected checkpoint θ⋆\n\nThe deployed checkpoint is selected by\nθ⋆ = θs⋆ ,\n\ns⋆ = arg min V (θs ).\n\n(13)\n\ns\n\nThe true lost packets L are excluded from both training and\nvalidation; they are used only for final evaluation. Algorithm 3\nsummarizes the procedure.\nIV. E VALUATION S ETTINGS\nThis section describes the pretrained backbones, datasets,\npacket-loss conditions, metrics, and implementation details\nused in the experiments. In all experiments, adaptation is\nperformed independently for each test waveform. The model\nis reset to the released public checkpoint before processing\nthe next waveform, so no information is transferred across\nevaluation utterances or recordings.\nA. Backbones\nWe evaluate TTT-PLC on two open-source PLC backbones.\nThe first is FRN [5], a full-band recurrent speech PLC model\nthat operates on STFT frames at 48 kHz. FRN processes the\nsignal frame by frame while maintaining recurrent state, and\navailable frames are passed through in the STFT domain. Only\n\n5\n\nframes marked as lost are replaced by the model prediction.\nFor FRN, we continue training with the released spectral\nobjective and evaluate both the non-causal adaptation procedure in Algorithm 1 and the causal block-replay procedure in\nAlgorithm 2.\nThe second backbone is PARCnet [6], a hybrid\nautoregressive-neural PLC model designed for real-time\nnetworked music. We use the released PARCnet checkpoint\nand retain the original AR-plus-neural architecture. Audio\nis mono at 32 kHz, each packet contains D = 320\nsamples, corresponding to 10 ms, and the model predicts a\nD + 80 = 400-sample window so that the final 80 samples\ncan be cross-faded against the subsequent buffer. The frozen\nPARCnet system combines a 10-packet AR context with\na 7-packet neural residual context. The neural residual is\nfaded in over 16 samples, and the combined AR-plus-neural\nprediction is faded out over the 80-sample tail. Available\npackets are passed through unchanged, and only packets\nindicated as lost by the trace are reconstructed.\nB. Datasets\nWe use separate speech and music evaluation settings to test\nlong-file adaptation, short-file speech PLC, in-domain music\nbehavior, and out-of-domain adaptation.\nLibriSpeech-40. LibriSpeech test-clean [31] is used\nto test whether adaptation can accumulate over long speech\nrecordings. We concatenate utterances by speaker to form 40\napproximately 8-minute files at 48 kHz. This setting is intentionally long: it exposes whether causal adaptation improves\nafter several received blocks and whether the adapted model\ndrifts later in the file. The same 40-speaker set is also used as\nthe out-of-domain speech condition for PARCnet.\nPLC Challenge 2022 speech. The PLC Challenge 2022 test\nset contains 966 short blind-test files at 16 kHz with real\npacket-loss traces from Microsoft Teams calls [3]. We use this\nbenchmark because it is a standard speech PLC evaluation set\nand because the files are short, which stresses the low-latency\nsetting where a causal replay method has limited time to adapt.\nPARCnet in-domain music. The in-domain music condition\nuses the MAESTRO recording used in the PARCnet paper [6],\n[32]. We evaluate the full 50-minute file, a 5-minute crop, and\nfive 30-second chunks at 32 kHz. PARCnet was trained on\nmusic data and is already well matched to this audio. This\ncondition tests whether test-time tuning can avoid harmful\nover-adaptation when the frozen model is already close to the\ntarget signal distribution.\nPARCnet out-of-domain speech. To evaluate adaptation under distribution shift, we apply PARCnet to LibriSpeech-40\nusing the same 32 kHz packet-loss interface. This setting is\ndeliberately out of domain for PARCnet and tests whether\nself-supervised adaptation from received packets can move a\nmusic-trained PLC model toward a new signal class without\nexternal data.\nC. Packet-loss conditions\nFor the LibriSpeech-40, FRN experiments, loss masks are\ntiled from PLC Challenge 2022 traces. The selected masks\n\n\f6\n\nIEEE/ACM TRANSACTIONS ON AUDIO, SPEECH, AND LANGUAGE PROCESSING\n\nspan loss rates from 0% to 70.5% and contain bursts from 1\nto 28 frames. For the PLC Challenge 2022 evaluation, we use\nthe official packet-loss traces as provided with the benchmark.\nThese traces are used without modification.\nFor the PARCnet experiments, we use nominal packet-loss\nrates of 10%, 20%, and 30%. Traces are generated once\nfor each file and loss rate using a fixed seed. The true lost\npackets are known as loss locations, but their clean samples\nare excluded from training and validation and are used only\nfor final evaluation. The PARCnet evaluation grid contains 141\nfile-rate cells: 40 LibriSpeech speakers times three loss rates,\nthe 50-minute MAESTRO file times three loss rates, the 5minute MAESTRO crop times three loss rates, and five 30second MAESTRO chunks times three loss rates.\nD. Metrics and aggregation\nFor FRN, we follow the evaluation protocol of the original\nFRN study and report STOI [17], wideband PESQ [16], logspectral distance (LSD), intrusive PLCMOS, and non-intrusive\nPLCMOS [4]. PESQ and PLCMOS are evaluated at 16 kHz.\nSTOI and LSD are computed at the native sampling rate of\neach corpus. On LibriSpeech-40, all five metrics are computed\non non-overlapping 20-second windows. The window scores\nare first averaged within each file and then averaged across\nthe 40 speakers. The 20-second windowing avoids PLCMOS\nlength limits and keeps the metric protocol consistent across\nall five metrics. On PLC Challenge 2022, the files are short\nenough to evaluate as complete files.\nFor PARCnet, we follow the objective evaluation protocol\nused in the original PARCnet study. The primary reconstruction metric is packet NMSE in dB, computed over true lost\npackets as\nNMSEpkt = 10 log10\n\n∥y − ŷ∥22\n,\n∥y∥22\n\n(14)\n\nwhere y is the ground-truth lost packet and ŷ is the reconstructed packet. Lower NMSE is better. We also report\nMel spectral convergence (Mel-SC) [33], which measures\nspectral error after applying a Mel-frequency filterbank to the\nmagnitude STFT. Following PARCnet, Mel-SC is computed\nusing 64 triangular Mel filters and a 512-sample Hann window with 50% overlap at the native 32 kHz sampling rate.\nTo include perceptual measures, we report PEAQ [34] and\nPLCMOS [4]. PEAQ is reported as Objective Difference Grade\n(ODG), averaged over non-overlapping 10-second windows\nafter resampling to 48 kHz. PLCMOS is the non-intrusive\nPLCMOS score, averaged over non-overlapping 10-second\nwindows after resampling to 16 kHz. We also track the\nsilence-energy ratio as a diagnostic guardrail for silence-fill\nartifacts. When confidence intervals are reported, they are 95%\nbootstrap intervals over per-file deltas.\nE. Implementation details\nFor FRN, the non-causal setting uses the full received file\nbefore final reconstruction and provides a per-file adaptation\nceiling. The causal setting uses block replay. In this setting, the\nmodel streams a block with the current parameters, emits the\n\ncorresponding audio, and then trains only on that completed\nblock. Updated weights affect only future blocks.\nFor LibriSpeech-40, causal FRN uses blocks of 3000\nframes, corresponding to 30-seconds, after a 1000-frame\nwarmup. For PLC Challenge 2022, causal FRN uses blocks of\n200 frames after a 200-frame warmup, matching the shorter\nfile duration. In both datasets, replay uses six epochs per block,\na 128-frame loss history, AdamW with learning rate 5 × 10−6 ,\nweight decay 10−6 , gradient clipping at L2 norm 2.0, and an\nL2 pull of strength 5 × 10−7 on the joiner parameters. The\nburst depth is anchored to observed packet losses,\nKburst = min (12, max (4, Kobs )) ,\n\n(15)\n\nwhere Kobs is the longest of the last ten completed real bursts.\nWe maintain exponential moving average (EMA) weights with\ncoefficient 0.99 and use this smoothed copy of the adapted\nmodel for streaming output.\nFor PARCnet, the proposed method is streaming everypacket TTT with held-out snapshot selection. We use AdamW\nwith learning rate 5×10−6 , weight decay 10−4 , one update per\navailable training packet, gradient clipping at L2 norm 2.0, and\nthe released PARCnet loss 100 · MSE + 0.5 · MR-STFT with\nper-packet normalization. A random 10% subset of available\npackets is held out before training using seed 42. These heldout packets are never used for gradient updates; they are used\nonly to select checkpoints using held-out packet NMSE. We\nevaluate snapshots every C updates, with C = 400 for the 40speaker headline experiments and C = 3200 for the 50-minute\nMAESTRO file. The same adaptation trajectory supports a\ncausal best-val mode, which uses only snapshots validated\nso far, and a two-pass best-val mode, which selects the best\nsnapshot over the whole file and reconstructs the true losses\nin a second pass. We also report single-pass oracle snapshot\nselection as an upper bound and multi-epoch adaptation as a\nquality-oriented configuration.\nThe PARCnet prediction window contains the target packet\nand an 80-sample tail. Because this tail can overlap a neighboring true loss, all PARCnet adaptation losses are computed\nwith a sample-level mask that excludes any samples belonging\nto true lost packets. This mask is applied to both the MSE and\nMR-STFT terms. Thus, clean audio at true loss positions is\nnever used during training or validation, even when it lies\ninside the prediction tail of an observed packet.\nV. R ESULTS\nIn this section, we evaluate our method, TTT-PLC, across\nspeech and music PLC, non-causal and causal deployment\nsettings, in-domain and out-of-domain signals, and multiple\npacket-loss rates. We first study FRN on long LibriSpeech\nrecordings and on the PLC Challenge 2022 test set to measure\nhow much of the non-causal adaptation gain can be recovered\nunder causality. We then evaluate PARCnet on out-of-domain\nspeech and in-domain music.\nA. FRN: non-causal ceiling and causal replay on long files\nTable I reports FRN results on LibriSpeech-40. The noncausal setting adapts using the full received file before the final\n\n\fDISSEN AND KESHET: TEST-TIME TUNING FOR PACKET LOSS CONCEALMENT\n\n7\n\nTABLE I\nFRN RESULTS ON L IBRI S PEECH -40 LONG FILES . E NTRIES ARE ABSOLUTE SCORES ; PARENTHESES GIVE THE CHANGE FROM FROZEN AND THE NUMBER\nOF IMPROVED FILES . T HE CAUSAL CONFIDENCE ROW GIVES 95% BOOTSTRAP CONFIDENCE INTERVALS FOR THE CHANGE FROM FROZEN .\n\nMethod\nFrozen FRN\nNon-causal\nCausal replay\nCausal 95% CI\nCausal/non-causal gain\n\nSTOI ↑\n\nPESQ ↑\n\nLSD ↓\n\nPLCMOS-I ↑\n\nPLCMOS-NI ↑\n\n0.911\n0.920 (+0.0092; 39/40)\n0.919 (+0.0078; 39/40)\n[+0.0054,+0.0104]\n85%\n\n2.442\n2.489 (+0.047; 38/40)\n2.482 (+0.040; 38/40)\n[+0.0313,+0.0485]\n84%\n\n1.036\n0.737 (-0.299; 39/40)\n0.732 (-0.304; 39/40)\n[-0.4047,-0.2153]\n102%\n\n2.661\n2.706 (+0.045; 32/40)\n2.696 (+0.035; 32/40)\n[+0.0164,+0.0524]\n77%\n\n2.589\n2.631 (+0.042; 31/40)\n2.626 (+0.037; 30/40)\n[+0.0228,+0.0518]\n88%\n\nreconstruction, and therefore serves as a per-file adaptation\nceiling. Causal replay is more constrained: it emits each block\nbefore replay training is performed, and updated parameters\ncan affect only future blocks. Because FRN is recurrent and\nreal losses often occur in bursts, replay training uses short\nsynthetic bursts rather than only isolated single-frame masks;\nwe refer to this part of the adaptation as burst-aware. Despite\nthe causal restriction, causal replay recovers most of the noncausal gain. It reaches 84–85% of the non-causal improvement\non STOI and PESQ, 77–88% on the two PLCMOS heads,\nand slightly exceeds the non-causal LSD gain. The bootstrap\nconfidence intervals in Table I show that these gains are\nconsistent across files.\nFigure 1 shows how the causal gains evolve over time in the\nlong LibriSpeech-40 files. During the first 30-seconds block,\nthe output is identical to frozen FRN because no replay update\nhas occurred. After the first completed block is replayed,\nthe next block immediately improves across the metrics. By\nroughly 60–70 seconds, the method reaches a stable plateau\nand later block boundaries provide smaller refinements, with\nno visible late-file drift.\nB. FRN: PLC Challenge 2022 test set\nTable II evaluates the same FRN adaptation idea on the 966file PLC Challenge 2022 test set. This benchmark contains\nmuch shorter files than LibriSpeech-40, so the amount of\ncausal adaptation time is limited. Even in this setting, causal\nreplay improves every metric relative to frozen FRN.\nThe confidence intervals in Table II show that the improvements are stable across the 966-file test set. Together with\nthe LibriSpeech-40 results, this shows that burst-aware block\nreplay on received packets improves FRN in both long-file and\nshort-file speech PLC settings.\nC. FRN runtime\nTable III reports FRN timing on a representative\nLibriSpeech-style file. Here, EMA denotes the exponential\nmoving average weight copy used for reconstruction. The\nabsolute real-time factors come from an unoptimized frameby-frame Python implementation and should be interpreted\nmainly as relative costs. Causal replay has a wall-clock cost\ncomparable to the six-epoch non-causal configuration because\nboth perform repeated replay training. Its advantage in this\nimplementation is causal validity rather than lower compute:\nemitted samples are never revised, and each replay update\naffects only future blocks.\n\nD. PARCnet: per-file test-time training\nWe next evaluate TTT-PLC on PARCnet. The adaptation\nprocedure follows the no-leak construction in Section III-C:\nonly received packets are used for training and held-out\nvalidation, while true lost packets are used only for final\nevaluation. We use LibriSpeech-40 as an out-of-domain speech\ncondition and the MAESTRO solo-piano recording from the\nPARCnet evaluation as the in-domain music condition.\nWe compare frozen PARCnet with three held-out-selection\nvariants. Causal best-val conceals each lost packet using the\nbest snapshot validated so far in the stream. Two-pass best-val\nselects the best snapshot after a full adaptation pass and then\nreconstructs the file with that checkpoint. Multi-epoch bestval extends the same selection rule across multiple adaptation\nepochs and represents the offline, quality-oriented setting. We\nalso report an oracle selector that chooses the best snapshot\nusing the true lost packets; this is an upper bound and is not\ndeployable.\n1) Out-of-domain and in-domain evaluation: Table IV reports the out-of-domain LibriSpeech results. Frozen PARCnet\ngives little packet-NMSE improvement relative to zero-fill,\nranging from −0.06 to +0.30 dB across the three packetloss rates. Causal best-val and two-pass best-val both substantially reduce packet NMSE. Two-pass best-val reaches\n−1.84, −1.76, and −1.59 dB at 10%, 20%, and 30% packet\nloss, respectively, while causal best-val reaches −1.63, −1.57,\nand −1.39 dB. Multi-epoch best-val gives the largest packetNMSE reductions in this condition, reaching −2.46, −2.34,\nand −2.04 dB.\nTable V reports the in-domain MAESTRO results on the 50minute piano file. Frozen PARCnet is already strong in this\ncondition, with packet NMSE between −4.28 and −5.28 dB\nacross packet-loss rates. The single-pass held-out selectors\nremain close to frozen and provide modest additional packetNMSE improvements: causal best-val reaches −5.52, −5.12,\nand −4.40 dB at 10%, 20%, and 30% loss, respectively, while\ntwo-pass best-val reaches −5.59, −5.08, and −4.43 dB. The\nsingle-pass oracle is only slightly better, indicating that heldout selection leaves little single-pass selection gain unused in\nthis in-domain setting. Multi-epoch adaptation further reduces\npacket NMSE at all three loss rates, reaching −5.94, −5.49,\nand −4.55 dB, although the perceptual metrics remain mixed.\nThus, the MAESTRO results show that held-out adaptation can\nimprove packet-level reconstruction even when the frozen indomain model is already strong, with the largest gains obtained\nby the offline multi-epoch setting.\n\n\f8\n\nIEEE/ACM TRANSACTIONS ON AUDIO, SPEECH, AND LANGUAGE PROCESSING\n\nTABLE II\nFRN RESULTS ON THE 966- FILE PLC C HALLENGE 2022 TEST SET. E NTRIES ARE ABSOLUTE SCORES ; PARENTHESES GIVE THE CHANGE FROM FROZEN\nAND THE WIN RATE . T HE CAUSAL CONFIDENCE ROW GIVES 95% BOOTSTRAP CONFIDENCE INTERVALS FOR THE CHANGE FROM FROZEN .\n\nSTOI ↑\n\nPESQ ↑\n\nLSD ↓\n\nPLCMOS-I ↑\n\nPLCMOS-NI ↑\n\n0.8854\n0.8910 (+0.0056; 70%)\n[+0.0040,+0.0078]\n\n2.2816\n2.3706 (+0.089; 86%)\n[+0.0786,+0.1001]\n\n2.1756\n1.9776 (-0.198; 79%)\n[-0.2178,-0.1782]\n\n2.7732\n2.9092 (+0.136; 74%)\n[+0.1199,+0.1529]\n\n2.6672\n2.9352 (+0.268; 81%)\n[+0.2390,+0.2966]\n\nMethod\nFrozen FRN\nCausal replay\nCausal 95% CI\n\nTABLE III\nFRN RUNTIME ON A L IBRI S PEECH - STYLE FILE , SINGLE GPU. RTF IS\nCOMPUTE TIME DIVIDED BY AUDIO DURATION ; LOWER IS FASTER .\nConfiguration\n\nRTF ↓\n\nRelative RT\n\nFrozen FRN\nSingle-pass causal\nNon-causal anchored, no EMA\nNon-causal anchored+EMA\n\n0.31\n0.66\n4.34\n4.70\n\n3.2×\n1.5×\n0.23×\n0.21×\n\n2) Held-out snapshot selection: To evaluate the quality of\nheld-out model selection, we compare best-val selection with\nan oracle selector that chooses, from the same single-pass\nadaptation trajectory, the snapshot minimizing packet NMSE\non the true lost packets. The oracle uses clean loss-region\naudio and is therefore not deployable; it is used only as an\nupper bound on snapshot selection within a fixed adaptation\ntrajectory. Across all 141 file-rate cells, held-out selection is\nwithin a mean 0.02 dB of this oracle, with median difference\n0.000 dB. It selects the exact oracle snapshot in 86 of 141 cells,\nand the largest observed gap is 0.41 dB. These results indicate\nthat validation on held-out received packets is an accurate\nproxy for selecting snapshots without using the unavailable\nclean lost packets.\n3) Causal algorithm deployment: The causal best-val mode\nuses only snapshots that have already been validated at the\ntime each lost packet is concealed. On the out-of-domain\nspeech condition, it trails two-pass best-val by approximately\n0.1–0.2 dB in packet NMSE, for example −1.63 versus\n−1.84 dB at 10% packet loss. On the in-domain MAESTRO\nfile, causal best-val remains close to both frozen and twopass best-val. Thus, most of the single-pass adaptation gain is\navailable even when future validation information is not used\nto reconstruct past losses.\nFigure 2 shows the position-dependent behavior on out-ofdomain LibriSpeech at r = 0.10. The causal curve starts closer\nto frozen because only early snapshots have been validated,\nbut it improves as more received packets become available\nand approaches the two-pass curve near the end of the file.\nThe two-pass and multi-epoch curves are comparatively stable\nover file position because they use selected checkpoints for\nreconstruction over the full file, with multi-epoch providing\nthe largest packet-NMSE improvement throughout.\n4) Multi-epoch adaptation: Running adaptation for five\nepochs and selecting the best snapshot across all epochs\ngives the strongest completed PARCnet configuration when\noffline adaptation time is available. On the held-out validation packets, the best snapshot across all epochs improves\nmedian packet NMSE by −0.40 dB relative to the single-\n\nepoch best snapshot, with a 95% confidence interval of\n[−0.48, −0.35] dB. The selected snapshot lies in epochs 4–5\nfor approximately 95% of cells, indicating that the validation\ntrajectory is still improving beyond the first pass.\nThe validation improvement also transfers to the true lost\npackets in the completed multi-epoch cells. Relative to the\nsingle-epoch best-val checkpoint from the same adaptation\nrun, the across-epoch selected checkpoint improves test packet\nNMSE by about 0.5 dB on average and improves every\nsetting. Table IV shows this effect on out-of-domain speech,\nwhere multi-epoch best-val gives lower packet NMSE than", "numLines": 500, "startLine": 500, "totalLines": 1534}}}
